    <text>
        <body>
            <head>131. Telegram From the <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of
                    State</orgName> to the <orgName corresp="rechbJf4QHaXNGzWb">Delegation</orgName>
                to the Nuclear and Space Talks in Geneva<note n="1" place="foot" type="source"
                    xml:id="d131fn1">Source: <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of
                        State</orgName>, Central Foreign Policy File, D870011-0780. Secret; <gloss
                        target="#t_EXDIS_1">Exdis</gloss>. Drafted in the White House; cleared by
                        <persName corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName>, Mahley, Nosenzo,
                    and in <gloss target="#t_SS_1">S/S</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_SSO_1"
                        >S/S-O</gloss>; approved by <persName corresp="recJYLsVHtwd9Q6nh"
                        >Adelman</persName>. Sent Immediate.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1986-05-02T23:22:00+00:00">May 2, 1986, 2322<gloss target="#t_Z_1"
                            >Z</gloss>
                    </date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>138815. Subject: (S) instructions for <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >US</placeName>/Soviet <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">nuclear and
                    space arms</rs> talks. Ref: (A) <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl"
                    >State</orgName> 012556;<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d131fn2">See <ref
                        target="#d126fn3">footnote 3, Document 126</ref>.</note> (B) <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> 54772;<note n="3" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d131fn3">In telegram 54772 to <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                    </gloss> Geneva, February 22, the <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl"
                        >Department</orgName> transmitted instructions for a response to <persName
                        corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName>’s proposals of January 14.
                        (<orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of State</orgName>, Central
                    Foreign Policy File, D860139-0610)</note> (C) <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> 55895;<note n="4" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d131fn4">In telegram 55895 to <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                    </gloss> Geneva, February 23, the <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl"
                        >Department</orgName> transmitted its preference that experts’ talks on
                        <orgName corresp="recWmlQ0xSSemmPRz">Risk Reduction Centers</orgName> be
                    held in Moscow or Washington. (<orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department
                        of State</orgName>, Central Foreign Policy File, D860431-0685)</note> (D) 85
                    <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> 288127.<note n="5"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d131fn5">In telegram 288127 to <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                    </gloss> Geneva, September 19, 1985, the <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl"
                        >Department</orgName> transmitted overall guidance for Round III of
                    Negotiations with the <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">
                        <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">USSR</placeName>
                    </gloss> on <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Nuclear and Space
                        Arms</rs>. (<orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of
                        State</orgName>, Central Foreign Policy File, D860048-1039)</note>
            </p>
            <pb facs="0555" n="528" xml:id="pg_528"/>
            <p>1. (S) Entire text.</p>
            <p>2. Following is guidance for <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                <orgName corresp="rechbJf4QHaXNGzWb">delegation</orgName> for the fifth round of
                negotiations with the <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">USSR</placeName>
                </gloss> on <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">nuclear and space
                arms</rs>, beginning May 1986. Guidance for previous rounds (Reftels) remains in
                effect, except as modified below. Specific guidance for each of the three
                negotiating groups is being provided septel.</p>
            <p>3. Principal objectives for Round V include:</p>
            <p>—Maintaining focus and priority on executing the mandate agreed at the last summit to
                pursue areas of common ground—50 percent <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reduction in strategic nuclear arms</rs>,
                appropriately applied and an <rs type="topic" corresp="recP1TxBSuFrpDZ2S"
                    >interim</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss> agreement;</p>
            <p>—Seeking elimination of Soviet linkages and preconditions, including their linkage of
                progress in <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> to an unacceptable ban on so-called <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recejU7I7gSPAJNQp">“space-strike” arms</rs>; their inclusion of
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> non-strategic forces under
                limits on <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic forces</rs>, and limits on
                    <gloss target="#t_UK_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec3Gz23Bw0AZRDOQ">UK</placeName>
                </gloss>/<placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> modernization and
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> cooperation with <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recydYSQ1GmGAh8yu">allies</rs> as preconditions
                for an <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss> agreement;</p>
            <p>—Focusing the discussions on the substance of <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >US</placeName> proposals;</p>
            <p>—Achieving progress on <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>
                concurrent with progress on reductions; and,</p>
            <p>—Emphasizing the problems for the <rs type="topic" corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl">arms
                    control</rs> process created by continuing Soviet non-<rs
                    corresp="recMjLDCnI9cLa32M" type="topic">compliance</rs>.</p>
            <p>4. Importance of Geneva process: the <orgName corresp="rechbJf4QHaXNGzWb"
                    >delegation</orgName> should again make clear to the Soviets (as in para 5 of
                reftel D) that the confidential Geneva talks are the appropriate forum for making
                progress on bilateral <rs type="topic" corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl">arms control</rs>
                issues.</p>
            <p>5. While again noting the agreement in the joint statement that, “during the
                negotiation of these agreements, effective measures for <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> will be agreed upon”,
                the <orgName corresp="rechbJf4QHaXNGzWb">delegation</orgName> should continue to
                emphasize the importance to the future of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl">arms control</rs> of <rs corresp="recMjLDCnI9cLa32M"
                    type="topic">compliance</rs> with existing <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl">arms control</rs> agreements, the need for the
                Soviets to correct non-compliant behavior, and <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> intent to take appropriate and
                proportionate responses in the absence of such corrective action.</p>
            <p>6. <orgName corresp="rechbJf4QHaXNGzWb">Delegation</orgName> should continue to
                resist strongly Soviet attempts to link progress in the three negotiating groups. In
                this regard, <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> del should also
                resist any Soviet attempts to erode the separate status and roles of the three
                negotiating groups, making clear that each group is fully competent both to explore
                policy issues and to commit governments on subjects within its areas of
                responsibility.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="rec8v6444Xqn7YB4U">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Whitehead</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
